  67:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****   // 20.3.1 base classes
  68:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****   /** @defgroup functors Function Objects
  69:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *  @ingroup utilities
  70:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *
  71:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *  Function objects, or _functors_, are objects with an `operator()`
  72:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *  defined and accessible.  They can be passed as arguments to algorithm
  73:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *  templates and used in place of a function pointer.  Not only is the
  74:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *  resulting expressiveness of the library increased, but the generated
  75:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *  code can be more efficient than what you might write by hand.  When we
  76:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *  refer to _functors_, then, generally we include function pointers in
  77:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *  the description as well.
  78:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *
  79:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *  Often, functors are only created as temporaries passed to algorithm
  80:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *  calls, rather than being created as named variables.
  81:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *
  82:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *  Two examples taken from the standard itself follow.  To perform a
  83:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *  by-element addition of two vectors `a` and `b` containing `double`,
  84:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *  and put the result in `a`, use
  85:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *  \code
  86:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *  transform (a.begin(), a.end(), b.begin(), a.begin(), plus<double>());
  87:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *  \endcode
  88:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *  To negate every element in `a`, use
  89:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *  \code
  90:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *  transform(a.begin(), a.end(), a.begin(), negate<double>());
  91:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *  \endcode
  92:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *  The addition and negation functions will usually be inlined directly.
  93:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *
  94:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *  An _adaptable function object_ is one which provides nested typedefs
  95:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *  `result_type` and either `argument_type` (for a unary function) or
  96:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *  `first_argument_type` and `second_argument_type` (for a binary function).
  97:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *  Those typedefs are used by function object adaptors such as `bind2nd`.
  98:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *  The standard library provides two class templates, `unary_function` and
  99:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *  `binary_function`, which define those typedefs and so can be used as
 100:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *  base classes of adaptable function objects.
 101:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *
 102:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *  Since C++11 the use of function object adaptors has been superseded by
 103:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *  more powerful tools such as lambda expressions, `function<>`, and more
 104:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *  powerful type deduction (using `auto` and `decltype`). The helpers for
 105:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *  defining adaptable function objects are deprecated since C++11, and no
 106:C:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Tools Arm Embedded/version13-3/arm-none-eabi/include/c++/13.3.1/bits\stl_function.h ****    *  longer part of the standard library since C++17. However, they are still
